description: From Middle English comen, cumen, from Old English cuman, from Proto-West Germanic *kweman, from Proto-Germanic *kwemaną (“to come”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷémt (“to step”), from *gʷem- (“to step”).

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Coming, arrival; approach.
examples: “If we count three before the come of thee, thwacked thou art, and must go to the women.”

entries.meaning: (vulgar, slang) Semen
examples: When a man uses a condom during sex, he takes all of his come with him, preventing her from getting pregnant.

entries.meaning: (vulgar, slang) Female ejaculatory discharge.
Used to indicate a point in time at or after which a stated event or situation occurs.
examples: Leave it to settle for about three months and, come Christmas time, you'll have a delicious concoction to offer your guests.
Come retirement, their Social Security may turn out to be a lot less than they counted on.
Come summer, we would all head off to the coast.

verbs.description: come (third-person singular simple present comes, present participle coming, simple past came or (now nonstandard) come, past participle come or (rare) comen)

definitionGroups.group: (intransitive) To move from further away to nearer to.

entries.meaning: To move towards the speaker.
examples: I called the dog, but she wouldn't come.
Stop dawdling and come here!

entries.meaning: To move towards the listener.
examples: Hold on, I'll come in a second.
You should ask the doctor to come to your house.

entries.meaning: To move towards the object that is the focus of the sentence.
examples: No-one can find Bertie Wooster when his aunts come to visit.
Hundreds of thousands of people come to Disneyland every year.

entries.meaning: (in subordinate clauses and gerunds) To move towards the agent or subject of the main clause.
examples: King Cnut couldn't stop the tide coming.
He threw the boomerang, which came right back to him.

entries.meaning: To move towards an unstated agent.
examples: The butler should come when called.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To arrive.
(intransitive) To appear, to manifest itself.
examples: The pain in his leg comes and goes.

entries.meaning: (with an infinitive) To begin to have an opinion or feeling.
examples: We came to believe that he was not so innocent after all.
She came to think of that country as her home.

entries.meaning: (with an infinitive) To do something by chance, without intending to do it.
examples: Could you tell me how the document came to be discovered?

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To take a position relative to something else in a sequence.
examples: Which letter comes before Y?   Winter comes after autumn.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, vulgar, slang) To achieve orgasm; to cum; to ejaculate.
examples: He came after a few minutes.
Come in me!

entries.meaning: (intransitive, of milk) To become butter by being churned.
(copulative, figuratively, with close) To approach a state of being or accomplishment.
examples: They came very close to leaving on time.   His test scores came close to perfect.
One of the screws came loose, and the skateboard fell apart.

entries.meaning: (figuratively, with to) To take a particular approach or point of view in regard to something.
examples: He came to SF literature a confirmed technophile, and nothing made him happier than to read a manuscript thick with imaginary gizmos and whatzits.

entries.meaning: (copulative, fossil word) To become, to turn out to be.
examples: He was a dream come true.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To be supplied, or made available; to exist.
examples: He's as tough as they come.
Our milkshakes come in vanilla, strawberry and chocolate flavours.
A new sports car doesn't come cheap.

entries.meaning: (slang) To carry through; to succeed in.
examples: You can't come any tricks here.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) Happen.
examples: This kind of accident comes when you are careless.

definitionGroups.group: (intransitive, with from or sometimes of) To have as an origin, originate.

entries.meaning: To have a certain social background.
To be or have been a resident or native.
examples: Where did you come from?

entries.meaning: To have been brought up by or employed by.
examples: She comes from a good family.
He comes from a disreputable legal firm.

entries.meaning: To begin (at a certain location); to radiate or stem (from).
examples: The river comes from Bear Lake.
Where does this road come from?

entries.meaning: (intransitive, of grain) To germinate.
(transitive, informal) To pretend to be; to behave in the manner of.
examples: Don’t come the innocent victim. We all know who’s to blame here.

entries.meaning: (typography, obsolete) Alternative form of comma in its medieval use as a middot ⟨·⟩ serving as a form of colon.
examples: Whoever introduced the several points, it seems that a full-point, a point called come, answering to our colon-point, a point called virgil answering to our comma-point, the parenthesis-points and interrogative-point, were used at the close of the fourteenth, or beginning of the fifteenth century.
